#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:158
msgid "Launch configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:160
msgid ""
"On the host side, `LaunchConfig` tells the runtime how to shape the grid:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:162
msgid ""
"use cuda_core::LaunchConfig;\n"
"\n"
"// Quick 1D launch: 256 threads per block, enough blocks to cover N "
"elements\n"
"let cfg = LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:169
msgid ""
"`for_num_elems` uses a block size of 256 and computes the grid size via "
"ceiling division -- the right default for most element-wise kernels. For "
"more control, construct `LaunchConfig` directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:173
msgid ""
"let cfg = LaunchConfig {\n"
"    grid_dim: (4, 4, 1),      // 4×4 = 16 blocks\n"
"    block_dim: (16, 16, 1),   // 16×16 = 256 threads per block\n"
"    shared_mem_bytes: 0,       // no dynamic shared memory\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:181
msgid ""
"Then pass it to the generated raw launch method. The call is unsafe because "
"`LaunchConfig` itself does not prove that hidden Y/Z dimensions are inactive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:184
msgid ""
"// SAFETY: `for_num_elems` is 1D and all three buffers contain N elements.\n"
"unsafe {\n"
"    module.vecadd(\n"
"        &stream,\n"
"        LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32),\n"
"        &a_dev,\n"
"        &b_dev,\n"
"        &mut c_dev,\n"
"    )\n"
"}\n"
".expect(\"Kernel launch failed\");\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:198
msgid "Or with the async API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:200
msgid ""
"// SAFETY: this is 1D, buffers contain N elements, and module/scheduler "
"share a context.\n"
"unsafe {\n"
"    module.vecadd_async(\n"
"        LaunchConfig::for_num_elems(N as u32),\n"
"        &a_dev,\n"
"        &b_dev,\n"
"        &mut c_dev,\n"
"    )\n"
"}?\n"
".sync()?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:215
msgid "Choosing block size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:217
msgid "The block size is the single most important tuning knob:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:219
msgid ""
"**256 threads** is a safe default. It balances occupancy (multiple blocks "
"per SM) with register pressure on most architectures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:221
msgid ""
"**Powers of 2** (128, 256, 512) align naturally with warp boundaries and "
"avoid wasting threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:223
msgid "**Too small** (< 128) may leave warp schedulers underutilized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:224
msgid ""
"**Too large** (1024) uses the full block thread limit, which may reduce the "
"number of concurrent blocks per SM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:227
msgid ""
"The grid size follows from the block size and the problem size: `grid_x = (N "
"+ block_x - 1) / block_x`. This is exactly what `LaunchConfig::"
"for_num_elems` computes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:231
msgid "Bounds checking"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:233
msgid ""
"Because the grid size is rounded up, some threads will have indices beyond "
"the array length. cuda-oxide's `DisjointSlice` handles this safely -- "
"`get_mut` returns `None` for out-of-bounds indices, so those threads simply "
"do nothing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:237
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn vecadd(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(idx) {   // out-of-bounds threads skip\n"
"        *c_elem = a[idx.get()] + b[idx.get()];\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-programming/execution-model.md:247
msgid ""
"This is a deliberate departure from CUDA C++, where bounds-checking is the "
"programmer's responsibility. cuda-oxide's approach eliminates an entire "
"class of out-of-bounds memory bugs at the cost of a single branch (which is "
"uniform across the warp for all but the last block)."
msgstr ""
